data.content:
Here's the full migration. Your code is the **timeout enforcement** pattern — it aborts a thread that exceeds a time limit. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`, so you must switch to cooperative cancellation.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

## What changed and why

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(() => work(), token)` | Task-based model; integrates with cancellation |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(token)` | Cancellation-aware waiting (.NET 6+ API) |
| `thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` | Cooperative cancellation replaces forced abort |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | No equivalent needed — cancellation is cooperative |

## Critical pitfall: uncooperative work

The fundamental limitation: **if `work()` is a long-running CPU-bound operation that never checks for cancellation, it will keep running even after the timeout fires.** The caller gets the `TimeoutException` promptly, but the background task continues until it finishes.

If `work` can be modified to accept a token, prefer this signature:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Then inside `work`, call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular checkpoints.

## If `work` truly cannot cooperate

Move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` — this is the only reliable way to forcibly terminate uncooperative code in modern .NET:

```csharp
// Last resort — out-of-process execution
var process = Process.Start("worker.exe", args);
if (!process.WaitForExit(timeout))
{
    process.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
    throw new TimeoutException(...);
}
```

## Other pitfalls to watch for

1. **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — it's `IDisposable`; leaking it leaks timers. Always `using`.
2. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** — the `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures you only catch *your* timeout, not some unrelated cancellation.
3. **`Task.WaitAsync` is .NET 6+** — if you ever need to target `netstandard2.0`, you'd need `Task.WhenAny(task, Task.Delay(timeout))` instead.
